rComments: He is an excellent prof. for students who want to learn the useful stuff. The downside for him is that students would get a good grade in his courses comparing to other courses.

Dr. Zingaro is magical. His knowledge is like a warm breeze filling my mind with goodness. You can imagine being on a beach coding with his voice like waves southing you to greatness. A beaver chews on wood, Dr. Z is like that beaver slowly cutting to the core of knowledge. A knowledge that is rough at first, then soft and tasty at its core.
Daniel, before kicking a first year student off the edge of a cliff, "THIS! IS! COMPU SCI!"

Daniel Zingaro is the Willie Wonka of computer science, and his students the oompa loompas. *Daniel singing softly, beautifully, "Come with me and you'll be in a world of" (his voice reaching falsetto) "pure imagination."

Like Butter - Dr. Zingaro's lectures are smooth like butter and just as rich and tasty. You can't handle that much richness everyday so take it sparingly like a delicious meal, I savoured his course. If you are on a COMP SCI lean diet avoid his course, you will get your fill of knowledge and make sure you are hungry to learn. Digest his brilliance.

Great prof, very clear with his answers and quite respected by the students. He's friendly and clearly knows his audience by trying to appeal to similar tastes of the average "computer science student". Cares about his students and wants them to do well but his tests are really hard

Its 2nd year proofs no one expects it to be easy, but Dan takes hard to another level as typical. Great lecturer for this course and you will fully understand concepts with him, requires a lot of office time though. Never slack off with this course as it will kill you His tests and assignments are brutal as usual with the 50s% averages.

He is a great guy and really approachable. But he makes the course 10x more difficult than it is. Averages were very close to 50%. I wouldn't take him again because I don't feel like I am learning well in the lectures. When he course coordinates the course, it will get extremely difficult.
Fun class. Extremely helpful teacher. Did assignments so much better thanks to him. Extremely friendly.

He is a absolute slice of apple pie. Like a warm summer breeze he enters the room, warming our hearts and minds with his thought provoking hot air.   He is the best professor I have ever had, hands down, and hands up, and hands waved in multiple directions.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Respected', 'Gives good feedback']

rComments: Dan is one of the most approachable profs I've had. He is very friendly and works hard for his students to feel welcome and to learn as much as they can. He does push you to work your hardest so be prepared for some difficult tests.
Great prof, very approachable

A prof that seriously shows that he cares for what he teaches. He's hilarious and genuinely entertaining to listen to. He's also really approachable. The course isnt really that hard if you understand, and if you don't, he tends to explain really well.
He is a great prof. My favourite so far :)
Legendary prof, best one I've had at UTM so far.
He will bore your brains out. Very slow to get to his point. AVOID.
Dan's, as always, a good prof. Expect lots of doable work and tough tests, but grading criteria are clear and you can definitely get an A if you try! He's willing to help you if you ask for it, too.
Very nice guy. Always ready to answer your questions and won't leave you hanging like other profs.
If you get this guy as your prof you're in luck. Easily the friendliest prof of UTM. Great professor too.
Awesome :)
Dan made the class really interesting. I had never done CS before his class, but he made me love it.
teacherRatingTags: ['Inspirational', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Lots of homework']

rComments: I really like Dan. He is there to hell you and has a discussion board that he constantly moderates. His lectures are clear but as far as the assignments go they are nothing like the examples. Often times they are significantly more difficult but that's to challenge you. We are computer scientists after all
